The offices include kindergarten, architects understood
The Avriopoint administration building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would expect to hide a minischool with everything that belongs to it - with colorful walls, imaginative furniture, a bunch of toys and even a miniature playground on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, it can be visited by children of Arch.Design employees.
Arch.Design, whose studios produced a number of important Brno buildings, has counted on the space for its corporate minischool since the first drawings of the Avriopoint building.
It employs almost 90 people mostly at the age of babyboom and cared that women designers and architects could quickly return to work.
Along with the possibility of abbreviated work, the kindergarten is a benefit that Arch.Design offers to its employees within the social program.
Builders and architects thus have the opportunity to combine demanding jobs with child care.
The minischool was invented by employees of Arch.Design themselves and with the support of leadership they managed to obtain a subsidy from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The corporate minischool is funded by the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to grant financing (subsidisation of CZK 2, 8 million), they were able to purchase equipment and equipment and provide qualified staff and operation for two years.
After the financial subsidy has been exhausted (2 years), Arch.Design has an obligation to operate a minischool at its own expense for 3 years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and the application for a subsidy was significantly helped by Economy Rating.
The care is provided by qualified staff, children are taken care of daily by a nurse and a teacher of the school, so children can attend kindergarten without age limit, yet most of them are over 3 years of age.
Since it is a "minimum school", only 5 children can be present at the same time, but even more will be replaced during the day.
The operation of the kindergarten is flexible according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use the kindergarten regardless of the hierarchy of the position in the company.
Although it is individual education and care, the programme content in the minischool is comparable to the framework programme for pre-school education.
Children not only play here, but they are also provided with quality teaching - from basic recognition to preparation to school benches, English language is also taught.
The class is equipped not only with toys, stimulating games, but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of young children directly in the company creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can check on their child at any time, and stress situations with delayed picking up children from kindergartens away from their parents ’ work are falling apart.
Thus, parents use working hours more productively.
No wonder there is a naturally loyal employee - employer relationship.
Arch.Design thus ranked with Czech companies, which offer significant benefits in recruiting new employees, are friendly to the family and through this program boosted personnel marketing.
The house of bones fascinates even after 100 years. Check the interiors of Gaudí
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the staircase resembles the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are open fish mouth.
This is the Casa Batlló house in Barcelona by Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Thanks to its organic shapes, the house earned the nickname House of Bones from the locals.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, tile fragments and mosaics, facade reminiscent of scales and ubiquitous soft curves, all typical of Antoni Gaudí's Art Nouveau.
The front of the house is played by dream lines, tender colors and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
In a detailed observation, geometry, rhythm and precisely thought-out order can be seen.
At night the entire facade of houses sounds even more dramatic, it is lit so that the impression of the gloss of colors is even enhanced.
The winding and twisting of shapes appear equally in the interiors.
Wood in waves copies window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, peepers and rails.
The Batlló House, which stands in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43, was created by the rebuilding of the 1877 house by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, rich industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on demolishing the old building and building a brand new one, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea for unusual and cheaper rebuilding.
The Casa Batlló apartment house was not designed by Antoni Gaudí himself.
He was co-operated by architect Josep Maria Jujol.
The decorations for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the use of mosaics on the facade were created on his design board.
A number of other creators and artists also worked on the facade.
Joint work on Casa Batlló's designs started with successful cooperation between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudí's house Casa Milá and the park Güell, in which there are other Gaudí's works.
From the locals soon to completion, the house earned the nickname "House of Bones" due to its organic shapes.
Others began to call it a "drowning house" because of the specific window opening mechanism.
It is also said that the sword of St. George, patron of Catalonia, is at the top of the building.
Hidden religious motifs also contain other sculptural elements of the structure.
Gaudí designed a unique central heating system with ventilation vents and typical chimneys for his time.
Bizarre may seem their forty-five-degree inclination.
In the creation of Gaudí, he did not completely respect the construction regulations of that time and did not allow them to bind him.
At the beginning of the construction, he obtained a building permit from the city, but the figures on the planned reconstruction were so vague that two years later, the city council was horrified by the result and demanded correction.
The council, for example, resented the fact that the construction interfered with the pillar and the public sidewalk.
The correction never happened, on the contrary: only fifteen days after the challenge of the city section, Josep Batlló requested (and successfully obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself moved to lower floors.
There was a social salon in the gallery on the second floor and a bedroom on the third floor and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented by a jewelry store.
The entire six-story house intersects the staircase, which can be ascended to the roof terrace itself.
The essential elements of the reconstruction were the abolition of all true angles and straight lines and their replacement with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The social part can be fully connected by opening the lounge doors and the larger society can communicate comfortably without retaining the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
Apart from the new facade, Gaudí's rebuilding house also acquired unconventional roofing and two additional floors.
Gaudí's game with light, blue and white glazed tiles is also impressive, with which the interior courtyard is covered, and skylights.
The game of two colors adds maximum light on all floors of the house.
Simply bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which absorbs the sun’s rays on the contrary.
The Casa Batlló House, which was included in the Unesco World Heritage Fund in 2005, can be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house, the most spacious and luxurious apartment is made available to the public.
The owners chose this step only in 2002, on the occasion of celebrating the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They remained at the tours as they found it to be a very advantageous business and, moreover, extended the tours with common and attic spaces, including the roof terrace.
Admission to the monument is definitely not negligible, it is EUR 16.50 and students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards have a 20% discount.
The sum significantly exceeds the price of admission to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to taste the real atmosphere of the house with dragon turrets, you must quickly become friends with some of the residents of the tenement and visit it directly at home.
