More and more parents want to watch people, so they want to keep an eye on their children.
Fear for their own child brings more and more people to the idea of GPS surveillance.
The system originally created for looking for cars can also monitor the movement of people, and thus help in such cases as the disappearance of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is about the size of a matchbox so far, but soon it can only be as big as clockwork.
A number of people were frightened by the missing Anička case and began to look for means to protect their children better.
Even at the cost of violating their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that it is not a spy, but another means of reducing the likelihood of any tragedy happening," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of surveillance equipment on the Czech market.
"I admit that in a certain case such devices may be misused, such as when they are put in a bag to someone who does not know about it, but we have not yet encountered such a case."
"Most of the customers actually buy it for security reasons," Pilin added.
According to him, a child should always know what the box is for and how it is used in an emergency.
Children's psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child doesn't want to wear anything like this, she'll just get rid of it.
"Even very young children show great creativity in how to deliberately lose things when they don't want to be under control."
"Big expectations had previously triggered mobile phones in parents, which, however, can be turned off just like these tracking devices," Bočková says.
According to her, it is also questionable whether such equipment would actually help in the event of an attack.
"As far as the kidnapping is concerned, the perpetrator practically always ensures that the child has no electronics that might reveal its location."
"Now it's a phone."
"When the tracking devices begin to expand, they will also be looking for them, because their sale will certainly be supported by massive advertising."
"In such a case, criminals will always be one step ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
However, it admits that a similar device can help in the event of sudden pedophile attacks.
According to Robert Čech, from RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and persons, even if an immediate destruction of a tracking device occurs after the attack, its presence may help.
"Equipment may be set to be sent periodically after a certain period of time."
"If it is damaged, at least the last position of the person concerned will be available."
"Dearer devices have built-in and tiltometers, so even if one just slipped and remained motionless, the machine will immediately send a warning with a positioning," says Bohemia.
According to him, a similar service can be carried out by smart mobile phones with navigation, where it is enough to upload special software.
The problem with current surveillance units is that they are either devices similar to matchbox size pendants or smaller mobile phones.
It's always the risk of losing them.
According to Pilin of Macro Weil, this is why the device now looks like a common digital watch is being tested.
"This will have the greatest advantage in that a potential aggressor may not recognize a tracking device at all".
"Or she won't recognize them until after a while and that can give the police extra time," she adds.
Whether the tracking devices develop into bracelets or pendants, they will still use the same technology as used to watch cars.
This is a combination of GPS positioning (which uses common autonavigation) and mobile phone functions that report the current position of the car.
