Longer index finger than ring finger indicates lower risk of cancer
Men who have an index finger longer than a ring finger are at less risk of becoming ill by prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British Cancer Magazine.
It could be related to the levels of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the finger can serve as a simple test of prostate cancer risk, especially for men under the age of 60," said the co-author of the study Ros Eeles, professor of the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could thus help determine which men should undergo a prostate cancer test, especially in combination with genetic risk or other threatening factors such as family health burdens, supplied by Eeles.
In the period 1994-2009, she followed with colleagues in Britain over 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and concurrently over three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had a index finger on their right hand shorter than a ring finger.
They had the same probability of prostate cancer as 19 percent of those whose fingers were as long.
However, in the case of those who had an index finger longer than a ring finger, this risk declined by 33 percent, even 87 percent for men under the age of 60.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers - formed in the prenatal period - apparently reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone matches the longer index finger.
Earlier research has shown that testosterone promotes growing prostate cancer.
The leading Czech geneticist and former President of the Academy of Sciences Professor Václav Pačes said for CTK that he knew this study briefly, but he does not seem to think that the relationship between the length of fingers and cancer was "completely proven".
