Cockell wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is unusual because it shows replacing one element with another element in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure," Cockell added.
It wasn't a random find.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Astrobiological Institute, who conducted the study, focused on Mono Lake because it shows high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically very similar elements, thus considering that microb, which is exposed to both elements, can be able to replace one after another.
"Arzen is poisonous mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to phosphorus".
"The result is that organisms can very hard to separate these elements from each other."
"However, arsenic is so different that just like phosphorus does not work. When it enters the organism, it starts working in biochemical processes," Anbar explained.
Scientists collect bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and expose them to an increasing concentration of arsenic that bacteria are able to adapt and grow.
