As is known, a few minutes before the end of the match (who had their team clearly won) named players one by one deliberately wasted time at the moment when the foul was to be played to provoke the judge, and he showed them a second yellow card.
In this way, both players will fulfill the prescribed penalty in the following match against Auxerre - with Real Madrid ending up in their group at the forefront - and will be able, stripped of cards, to continue to the next stage.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Commission awarded coach José Mourinh a two-game penalty and the guilty players received a cash penalty.
The provocation of the yellow card under similar conditions is not a new practice, but is more or less common in football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos of football, that is, rules that, although unwritten, follow each other.
Part of the discussion in this case came about because its participant was the Real Madrid team (who boasts generosity and honor in his anthem, and who has already fined his players for similar acts), and as it seems, also thanks to the drama led by Mourinh, who thus adds another episode to his long history of comedian and provocative.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this kind of action, which is not expressly prohibited by the rules, is contrary to the principles of sport, that is, whether there is circumvention of the law in these acts; indeed, it is actions that respect sports rules whose meaning seems to be trying to circumvent.
The type of damage such acts cause to the sports spirit is being resolved.
One of the features of sportsmanship is the physical integrity of opponents, which was not violated in these cases, so there was no violent play.
Another of these features characterizing a clean game is to avoid players having an advantage against the opponent's team because of their misdemeanors - which also did not happen here.
So the paradoxical thing about Real Madrid players' action is the fact that what we normally characterize as a ruse or circumvention of the law has not been a secret violation of the rules in order to avoid penalties, but this behavior should have been as evident as possible in order to receive the penalty.
They waited and liked to be punished.
Another question, however, is what advantage guilty of their deliberate transgressions will have.
It must be noted here that the opponent is not in a disadvantaged position and that in the current match he will not achieve any benefit, as the obvious consequence is that the team itself will have fewer players.
And it's not even a useful strategy for the next match, because the club won't be able to count on these players.
Clearly, the advantage is that players start the next stage of the Champions League without cards that could jeopardise their participation in the future match.
However, this is an advantage from a long-term perspective and with a degree of uncertainty, i.e. at first glance, the team can be eliminated, and in addition, by doing so, players will be punished, and they will go to the second round of cards in which one card less than in the first round is sufficient to exclude.
So as the wheels continue, it will not be entirely clear whether this is an advantage.
In short, these negotiations do not go against the sports spirit, which includes making strategic decisions that allow maximum benefit to be gained under the rules.
in the case we are dealing with here, players were not intended to avoid granting punishment (which would be a clear case of circumvention), but rather to choose when to submit to it.
They made strategic decisions without avoiding or running from punishment.
Although the line between wit and circumvention is not clear, I believe that in this case it was clearly a wit.
It seems to me that polemics arise for two reasons: because they were two self-exclusions and because of the way in which the transfer of instructions was carried out to provoke them from the leadership.
Damage to sports principles by these actions is not as ethical as aesthetic.
