The United States amends the rules for issuing visas
People will have to contact the Service Centres before interviewing the Consular Department; the costs will be lower and the waiting time will be reduced.
As of 10 January 2011, the visa negotiation process will change at the United States Embassy and consulates.
with the new procedure, most applicants will have to contact the Services Centre for Visa Applicants (abbreviated from ASC English) before interviewing the Consular Department.
The ASC personnel will collect biometric information from the applicant and will be evaluated by the Consular Department before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including the following:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, no longer need to pay the fee for arranging the meeting, the second for processing the application and more for the delivery of the document by the transport service.
The applicant shall pay only a single fee covering all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: an amount equivalent to $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with applications (including temporary workers visas) and $390 for a visa for traders and investors.
People who want to renew their visa will not have to interview a consular official, but will only contact the nearest ASC, where they will submit their documents and their fingerprints will be taken.
As biometric information will be collected in the ASC, applicants who will require a second meeting with an interview at the Consular Department will spend less time here than in the past.
Likewise, those who will apply for a visa at the consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an extra $26 service fee.
For further information on the new visa application, please visit the following website http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visa-FAQs.html
