Climate: how France hacked its promises of funding
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to test compliance with promises for quickly unblocked funding (said fast start funding) or premature financing, implemented by developed countries.
And the big French hacks have been revealed
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion in 2010-2012.
The European Union promised EUR 7.2 billion for three years and France EUR 1.26 billion (that is 420 million per year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU drew a big ace to convince its partners of the reality of its fast start funding commitment: a report detailing the action of its Member States, press conference, grand side event, distribution of brochures...
A transparent operation priceless and valued at its true value: developed countries and civil society would want all developed countries and civil society to do them the same and with the same degree of accuracy.
The EU announces that it released EUR 2.2 billion in 2010, bringing it on the right track to keep its promise of 7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we focus on the detail, we find that things are much more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, these funds are "new and additional" to ensure that the increased burden is put into effect without harming the Public Development Assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 as a reference: international funding has been preserved and it adds 150 million to it for three years to the title of fast start funding.
Other countries have selected similar references with annual payment dates or with public development aid levels.
By contrast, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" of 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous periods or to the global level Public aid for the development of d'Aide publique au développement.
Specifically, the overall amount of support from France towards developing countries may remain constant (or even decrease) to keep its commitment to financing "new and additional"...
Another crucial element is the division into donations and loans.
There is not yet a rule and everyone chooses their own method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that €1 borrowed is equal to €1 donated.
Clearly, it is hard to prove: efforts are not comparable.
If the use of loans can be demonstrated for some investments that are profitable (often projects related to the reduction of emissions, consisting of more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro that we receive as the equivalent of one euro that we give... , we should not see it as the basis of our commitments, but as the cost of the loan to a creditor country (i.e. the interest rate equivalent).
But France can only provide such a justification: it 'complys' with its €420 million commitment, making it 91.5% loan (€389.8 million) and 8.5% donations (€36.1 million) - see the EU document so that you can verify it for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union that makes use of the loan on such a scale.
Germany claimed 46% from there, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) adhere to their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts €1 to satisfy its promise, France only gives 10 centimes and considers this effort to be comparable.
A beautiful conjurer's piece!
For the summary, when financing a "fast start", France operates with double fraud: on the one hand with the development of the share over time and on the other hand with a real financial burden.
Although it only spends EUR 36.1 million, it can convince itself that it issues EUR 420 million "new and additional" in connection with its promises.
The manipulation of the Minister of Finance (as it seems that it is Bercy who made such decisions) could have a double negative impact, simultaneously within the EU (why would the Member States continue to donate when it is enough to lend?) and in negotiations, because developing countries are not completely naive...
The pre-financing chapter is just a small question, relatively short-term, in relation to the climate debate series.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in a huge machine like the UNFCCC.
Let's hope this isn't our case.
Whatever it is, it is necessary to draw knowledge from this first year of early funding.
First, France should announce the change in its way of keeping the accounting records for 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of respect for its obligations and decency and justice vis-à-vis other countries of the European Union.
But, above all, France should avoid discussing long-term funding contributions (another fundamental chapter currently discussed): we will not escape the issue of 'additionality' or the way in which loans are recorded.
France should change its position to become as progressive in these deposits as it is with others.
So everyone is putting hope into the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Koscius-Morizet, who arrives in Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement of France's fast start and its vision of 'additionality' and the use of loans could trigger an increase in the level of international confidence necessary to move forward in discussions.
An alarm about pesticides that children eat.
A ten-year-old child eats 81 different chemicals one day, according to one study published this Wednesday, from the Future Generations Association (ex- Movement for Rights and Conservation of Future Generations).
The Association, which notes that its results "have no significant statistical value with regard to the low number of samples analysed, but are characteristic of the processing issue", purchased food commonly consumed in four meals between July and September and one light meal as a light snack for one child roughly ten years in supermarkets in l'Oise and Paris.
These typical dishes, including official recommendations - five fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day - as well as sugar confectionery, were analysed by research laboratories on chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, 42 of which are classified as carcinogenic, possible or likely, and five substances are among clear carcinogens, as well as 37 substances that could act as disruptive to internal excretion glands (PE), according to studies by several institutions, such as the International Center for Cancer Research.
"Although in almost all cases the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, in our research we can well see that the reality in consumer exposure to contaminated substances, possibly carcinogenic, and/or PE is striking", says the Association.
For breakfast, butter and tea with milk contain by itself about ten résidies with possible carcinogenic effects and three proven to be certain carcinogens, as is the case with about twenty residues that could disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, reported by the study as a small snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including in France banned fungicide.
The same applies to the green beans from Kenya, included in lunch for which studies have discovered traces of strong insecticides banned in the EU.
In addition, minced meat steak, canned tuna, and even bagels and chewing gum were riddled with pesticides and other chemicals.
In water from the tap analysis revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
The salmon steak for dinner was "richest" with 34 discovered chemical residues and even an analysis of the plastic plate used to heat food in the microwave oven did not avoid analysis.
The final risk to consumers of this "contaminant cocktail" is likely underestimated", results from the study.
The Ecological Europe-Greening Society (EE-LV) proposed "to face an emergency situation" to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop the "growth of civilizational diseases".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) examined the situation of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.
